# Laravel Development Cursor Rules

## Project Structure & Organization

### Routing
- **Group routes** by functionality with clear naming conventions
- **Always use route names** instead of hardcoded URLs throughout the application
- **Apply route expressions** for parameter validation (e.g., `{id}` where `id` is numeric)
- **Link route groups to middlewares** appropriately (e.g., `auth`, `admin`, `api`)
- **Use resource controllers** for CRUD operations to maintain RESTful standards

```php
// Good
Route::middleware(['auth'])->name('admin.')->prefix('admin')->group(function () {
    Route::resource('users', UserController::class);
    Route::get('dashboard', [DashboardController::class, 'index'])->name('dashboard');
});

// Bad
Route::get('/admin/users', 'UserController@index');
Route::post('/admin/users', 'UserController@store');
```

### Modular Organization
- **Organize files into modules** based on functionality rather than keeping all files in the same folder
- Follow domain-driven design principles for large applications
- Structure: `app/Modules/{ModuleName}/{Controllers,Models,Services,Repositories}`

## Validation

### Form Request Validation
- **Always use Form Request classes** for validation instead of inline validation in controllers
- **Implement Laravel Precognition** or similar packages for automatic frontend validation generation
- **Display validation errors** in Blade templates for each form field

```php
// Good - Form Request
public function store(StoreUserRequest $request)
{
    // Controller logic here
}

// Bad - Inline validation
public function store(Request $request)
{
    $validated = $request->validate([
        'name' => 'required|string',
    ]);
}
```

### Custom Validation Rules
- **Create custom rule classes** for complex validation logic instead of inline closures
- Place custom rules in `app/Rules` directory

## Data Handling

### Collections
- **Use Laravel Collections** for complex array operations
- Leverage built-in collection methods instead of manual array manipulation

```php
// Good
$filtered = collect($data)->filter()->map()->toArray();

// Bad
$filtered = [];
foreach($data as $item) {
    // Manual filtering
}
```

### DataTables
- **Use Yajra DataTables** as the default standard for table listings
- Configure DataTable settings at the PHP level
- Implement server-side processing for large datasets

## Frontend Integration

### JavaScript Management
- **Include JS files individually** in each Blade template
- Compile and add to main scripts file at runtime
- Use Laravel Mix/Vite for asset compilation

### Blade Templates
- **Never use `<?php ?>` tags** - use Blade directives instead (`@php`, `@if`, `@isset`)
- **Use Laravel's flash messaging** system for notifications
- **Implement Toastr** for user-friendly notification display

```blade
{{-- Good --}}
@php
    $variable = 'value';
@endphp

{{-- Bad --}}
<?php $variable = 'value'; ?>
```

## Error Handling & Logging

### Exception Handling
- **Wrap every function** in its own try-catch block
- Use multiple try-catch blocks when necessary for granular error handling

```php
public function processData()
{
    try {
        // Main logic
    } catch (SpecificException $e) {
        // Handle specific exception
    } catch (\Exception $e) {
        // Handle general exception
    }
}
```

### Logging
- **Split log files** by date and functionality
- Use channels for different log types
- Configure in `config/logging.php`

```php
Log::channel('daily')->info('User action', ['user_id' => $userId]);
```

## File Management

### Storage
- **Use Laravel's Storage facade** for all file operations
- **Store all files in the storage folder**, never in public directly
- **Create symbolic links** for publicly accessible files
- Use `storage_path()` and `Storage::disk()` appropriately

```php
// Good
Storage::disk('public')->put('avatars', $file);

// Bad
$file->move(public_path('uploads'), $filename);
```

## Performance Optimization

### Queues
- **Convert time-consuming tasks to queued jobs**
- **Use Supervisor** on production servers following official Laravel documentation
- **Implement unique constraints** and avoid overlaps for queue jobs

```php
// Job class
class ProcessPayment implements ShouldQueue, ShouldBeUnique
{
    use Dispatchable, InteractsWithQueue, Queueable;
}
```

### Task Scheduling
- **Use Laravel's task scheduler** for all cron jobs
- Define schedules in `app/Console/Kernel.php`
- Implement `withoutOverlapping()` for long-running tasks

## Authentication & Authorization

### Authentication
- **Use Laravel Breeze** as the default authentication scaffolding
- **Create separate tables and guards** for different user types when schemas differ significantly

```php
// config/auth.php
'guards' => [
    'admin' => [
        'driver' => 'session',
        'provider' => 'admins',
    ],
],
```

### Authorization
- **Implement Spatie Permission package** for role-based access control
- **Define permissions in both Blade templates and Controller constructors**

```php
// Controller
public function __construct()
{
    $this->middleware('permission:edit-users')->only(['edit', 'update']);
}
```

```blade
{{-- Blade --}}
@can('edit-users')
    <button>Edit User</button>
@endcan
```

## Database Operations

### Transactions
- **Wrap related database operations** in a single transaction
- **Always implement rollback** in catch blocks

```php
DB::beginTransaction();
try {
    // Multiple database operations
    DB::commit();
} catch (\Exception $e) {
    DB::rollBack();
    throw $e;
}
```

### Migrations & Seeding
- **Use migrations exclusively** for schema changes (Code-first approach)
- **Never modify the database directly** outside of migrations
- **Use seeders** for static data (admin users, countries, zip codes)

### Eloquent ORM
- **Prioritize Eloquent ORM** over Query Builder
- **Only use Query Builder** when Eloquent cannot achieve the required functionality
- Keep database queries in Model methods, not in Controllers

```php
// Good - In Model
public function scopeActive($query)
{
    return $query->where('status', 'active');
}

// Usage in Controller
$users = User::active()->get();
```

## Code Architecture

### Design Patterns
- **Use Helper functions** for globally accessible functionality
- **Implement PHP Traits** for sharing methods between multiple classes
- **Build Service classes** to leverage Dependency Injection
- **Follow MVC pattern strictly**: Models for database, Views for HTML, Controllers for logic
- **Use Facades** for better code clarity when accessing services
- **Implement Events and Listeners** for decoupled actions (e.g., user registration triggers email, logging)
- **Use Singleton pattern** for classes that should be initialized once

### Dependency Injection
```php
// Good - Dependency Injection
public function __construct(UserService $userService)
{
    $this->userService = $userService;
}

// Bad - Direct instantiation
public function index()
{
    $userService = new UserService();
}
```

## Configuration & Security

### Environment Variables
- **Access env variables through config files only**
- **Define constants** for static values used throughout the application
- **Never use `env()` helper outside config files**

```php
// config/app.php
'api_key' => env('API_KEY'),

// In code
$apiKey = config('app.api_key');
```

### Security
- **Include CSRF tokens** in all forms including AJAX requests
- Use `@csrf` directive in forms
- Include token in AJAX headers

```javascript
// AJAX with CSRF
$.ajaxSetup({
    headers: {
        'X-CSRF-TOKEN': $('meta[name="csrf-token"]').attr('content')
    }
});
```

## API Response Standards

### Response Structure
- **Standardize API responses** with consistent structure:

```php
return response()->json([
    'success' => true,
    'code' => 200,
    'message' => 'Operation successful',
    'data' => $result
]);
```

- **Use specific response codes** for different scenarios
- Implement a base API controller with standardized response methods

## Real-time Features

### Broadcasting
- **Use Laravel's built-in broadcasting** with WebSockets for real-time features
- Configure with Pusher, Laravel WebSockets, or Socket.io
- Implement presence channels for user tracking

```php
// Broadcasting an event
broadcast(new OrderShipped($order))->toOthers();
```

## Code Quality Rules

### Naming Conventions
- Use PascalCase for classes
- Use camelCase for methods and variables
- Use snake_case for database columns and route names
- Use kebab-case for URLs

### Comments & Documentation
- Document complex logic with clear comments
- Use PHPDoc blocks for methods and classes
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes

### Testing
- Write feature tests for all major functionalities
- Write unit tests for service classes and complex methods
- Maintain minimum 80% code coverage

## Performance Best Practices

### Database Optimization
- Always eager load relationships to avoid N+1 queries
- Use database indexing for frequently queried columns
- Implement caching for static or rarely changing data

```php
// Good - Eager loading
$users = User::with('posts', 'comments')->get();

// Bad - N+1 problem
$users = User::all();
foreach($users as $user) {
    echo $user->posts; // Triggers query for each user
}
```

### Caching
- Implement Redis/Memcached for session and cache storage
- Cache expensive queries and computations
- Use cache tags for granular cache invalidation

## Deployment Checklist

- [ ] Run `composer install --optimize-autoloader --no-dev`
- [ ] Run `php artisan config:cache`
- [ ] Run `php artisan route:cache`
- [ ] Run `php artisan view:cache`
- [ ] Set `APP_ENV=production` and `APP_DEBUG=false`
- [ ] Configure Supervisor for queue workers
- [ ] Set up SSL certificates
- [ ] Configure backup strategies
- [ ] Set up monitoring and logging
- [ ] Configure rate limiting
